  "prompt": "What is the sum of all the integers less than 100 which leave a remainder 2 when divided by 5?",
  "response": "To find the sum of all integers less than 100 that leave a remainder of 2 when divided by 5, we first identify these integers.\n\nThese integers can be expressed in the form \\(5k + 2\\), where \\(k\\) is a non-negative integer. We need to find \\(k\\) such that \\(5k + 2 < 100\\).\n\n1. Let's solve for \\(k\\):\n   \\[\n   5k + 2 < 100 \n   \\]\n   \\[\n   5k < 98 \n   \\]\n   \\[\n   k < 19.6 \n   \\]\n   Hence, \\(k\\) can range from 0 to 19 (since \\(k\\) must be an integer).\n\n2. The numbers are:\n   \\[\n   5(0) + 2 = 2, \n   5(1) + 2 = 7, \n   5(2) + 2 = 12, \n   \\ldots,\n   5(19) + 2 = 97\n   \\]\n\n3. We can write the sequence explicitly: \\(2, 7, 12, 17, 22, \\ldots, 97\\).\n\nThis sequence is an arithmetic progression with the first term \\(a = 2\\) and common difference \\(d = 5\\). The sum of the first \\(n\\) terms of an arithmetic progression can be found using the formula:\n   \\[\n   S_n = \\frac{n}{2} \\left(2a + (n - 1) d\\right)\n   \\]\n\nWe need to verify the number of terms (\\(n\\)). We know \\(a_n = 97\\) is the last term.\nUsing the \\(n\\)-th term formula for an arithmetic sequence \\(a_n = a + (n-1)d\\):\n\n   \\[\n   97 = 2 + (n-1)5\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   97 = 2 + 5n - 5\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   97 = -3 + 5n\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   100 = 5n\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   n = 20\n   \\]\n\nNow we use the sum formula:\n   \\[\n   S_{20} = \\frac{20}{2} \\left(2 \\cdot 2 + (20-1) \\cdot 5\\right)\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   S_{20} = 10 (4 + 95)\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   S_{20} = 10 \\cdot 99\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   S_{20} = 990\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, the sum of all integers less than 100 which leave a remainder of 2 when divided by 5 is 990.",
